\section{Recursive Partitioning Foundations}\label{sec:5.1}

This section fixes the tree function class: axis-aligned partitions of the feature space, with a constant prediction in each cell.

\subsection{Trees as axis-aligned partitions}\label{sec:5.1.1}

A decision tree encodes a recursive partition of the feature space and a constant prediction in each cell. The feature space is $\mathcal{X} = \mathbb{R}^p$ throughout the unit; the prediction space $\mathcal{Y}$ is $\mathbb{R}$ for regression and $\{1, \ldots, K\}$ (or, for probability outputs, the $K$-simplex) for $K$-class classification.

\begin{definition}[Binary decision tree]\label{def:bin-tree}
A \emph{binary decision tree} is a finite rooted tree $T$ in which every node has either zero children (a \emph{leaf}) or exactly two (an \emph{internal node}); the unique node with no parent is the \emph{root}. The tree carries the following labels:
\begin{itemize}
\item every internal node $t$ has a \emph{split rule} $(j_t, s_t)$ with $j_t \in \{1, \ldots, p\}$ and $s_t \in \mathbb{R}$, routing an input $x \in \mathcal{X}$ to the \emph{left} child when $x_{j_t} \leqslant s_t$ and to the \emph{right} child otherwise;
\item the leaves are enumerated $m = 1, \ldots, M$ where $M = |T|$, and each leaf $m$ has a \emph{leaf value} $c_m \in \mathcal{Y}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Region induced by a leaf]\label{def:induced-partition}
For each leaf $m$, let $\mathcal{R}_m \subseteq \mathcal{X}$ be the set of inputs that reach $m$ when the split rules of Definition~\ref{def:bin-tree} are applied from the root. Each $\mathcal{R}_m$ is an axis-aligned rectangle (a finite intersection of half-spaces $\{x : x_j \leqslant s\}$ and $\{x : x_j > s\}$); the family $\{\mathcal{R}_m\}_{m=1}^{M}$ partitions $\mathcal{X}$.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Tree predictor]\label{def:tree-predictor}
The \emph{predictor} encoded by a tree $T$ with leaf values $\{c_m\}_{m=1}^{M}$ is the piecewise-constant function
\[
  f_T(x) \;=\; \sum_{m=1}^{M} c_m \, \indc\{x \in \mathcal{R}_m\}, \qquad x \in \mathcal{X}.
\]
The \emph{tree class} on $\mathcal{X}$ is
\[
  \mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{tree}} \;=\; \bigl\{f_T : T \text{ is a binary decision tree on } \mathcal{X}\bigr\}.
\]
\end{definition}

Three structural facts will recur:

\begin{itemize}
\item The partition $\{\mathcal{R}_m\}$ is determined by the splits alone; the leaf values $c_m$ play no role in selecting splits.
\item Once the partition is fixed, leaf values minimize the loss separately in each cell, in closed form for the losses used in this unit.
\item $\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{tree}}$ contains every function that is constant on the cells of some axis-aligned rectangular partition of $\mathcal{X}$. Such piecewise-constant functions are dense in $L^2(P)$ for any $P$ with bounded support, and on a finite sample of size $n$ a tree with $n$ leaves interpolates any labels exactly. An unconstrained tree class therefore overfits any finite sample, and some form of capacity control is mandatory.
\end{itemize}

\begin{example}[A two-feature tree and its partition]\label{ex:two-feature-tree}
A three-leaf tree on $[0, 1]^2$ with split rules
\[
  \text{root: } x_1 \leqslant 0.5 \;\to\; A; \qquad \text{else: } x_2 \leqslant 0.3 \;\to\; B \text{ else } C
\]
induces the partition $\mathcal{R}_A = \{x_1 \leqslant 0.5\}$, $\mathcal{R}_B = \{x_1 > 0.5,\; x_2 \leqslant 0.3\}$, $\mathcal{R}_C = \{x_1 > 0.5,\; x_2 > 0.3\}$. The figure below renders the three regions.

<<two-feature-partition, fig.width=4.0, fig.height=3.5, out.width="0.55\\linewidth", echo=FALSE>>=
par(mar = c(4, 4, 0.5, 0.5))
plot(NA, xlim = c(0, 1), ylim = c(0, 1),
     xlab = expression(x[1]), ylab = expression(x[2]), asp = 1)
rect(0,   0,   0.5, 1,   col = "#EFF6FF", border = NA)
rect(0.5, 0,   1,   0.3, col = "#FEF3C7", border = NA)
rect(0.5, 0.3, 1,   1,   col = "#F0FDF4", border = NA)
abline(v = 0.5); segments(0.5, 0.3, 1, 0.3)
text(0.25, 0.5, "A"); text(0.75, 0.15, "B"); text(0.75, 0.65, "C")
@
\end{example}

\begin{suppremark}[Why axis-aligned]
Axis-aligned splits are one modeling choice; oblique trees, which split on linear combinations $\beta^\top x \leqslant s$, also fit Definition~\ref{def:bin-tree}. The axis-aligned restriction has two practical consequences. First, the best-split search at a node decomposes into $p$ separate one-dimensional sweeps, which keeps greedy growing tractable for $p$ in the hundreds. Second, the predictor is invariant to monotone feature transformations: training on $\phi(x_j)$ in place of $x_j$ for any monotone increasing $\phi$ yields the same partition and predictions. This invariance is why tree models skip the standardization step that ridge, lasso (Unit~2 \S 2.7.1), logistic regression, and SVM require.
\end{suppremark}

\subsection{Empirical risk on a partition}\label{sec:5.1.2}

Fix a tree $T$ with regions $\{\mathcal{R}_m\}_{m=1}^{M}$ from Definition~\ref{def:induced-partition}. Given a loss $\ell : \mathcal{Y} \times \mathcal{Y} \to \mathbb{R}_{\geqslant 0}$ (Unit~1 Definition~1.17) and training rows $\{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^{n}$, write
\[
  I_m \;:=\; \{i : x_i \in \mathcal{R}_m\}, \qquad n_m \;:=\; |I_m|
\]
for the index set and count of training rows that reach leaf $m$.

\begin{lemma}[Per-leaf decomposition of empirical risk]\label{lem:perleaf-decomp}
The empirical risk of the tree predictor $f_T$ (Definition~\ref{def:tree-predictor}) on the training sample is
\[
  \widehat{\mathcal{R}}_n(f_T) \;=\; \frac{1}{n} \sum_{m=1}^{M} \sum_{i \in I_m} \ell(y_i, c_m).
\]
The leaf values $\{c_m\}_{m=1}^{M}$ separate: minimizing $\widehat{\mathcal{R}}_n(f_T)$ over the leaf values reduces to
\[
  c_m^* \;\in\; \arg\min_{c \in \mathcal{Y}} \sum_{i \in I_m} \ell(y_i, c)
\]
solved independently for each $m$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
By Definition~\ref{def:tree-predictor}, $f_T(x_i) = c_m$ for the unique leaf $m$ with $x_i \in \mathcal{R}_m$ (the regions partition $\mathcal{X}$, Definition~\ref{def:induced-partition}). Each training index $i \in \{1, \ldots, n\}$ therefore lies in exactly one $I_m$, so
\[
  \widehat{\mathcal{R}}_n(f_T) \;=\; \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \ell(y_i, f_T(x_i)) \;=\; \frac{1}{n} \sum_{m=1}^{M} \sum_{i \in I_m} \ell(y_i, c_m).
\]
The double sum has the form $\sum_m g_m(c_m)$ with $g_m(c) := \sum_{i \in I_m} \ell(y_i, c)$; minimization separates over the $c_m$.
\end{proof}

The per-leaf optimum has a closed form for the three losses used in this unit.

\begin{example}[Closed-form leaf values]\label{ex:closed-form-leaf}
For a fixed partition with leaf row counts $\{n_m\}_{m=1}^{M}$:

\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Squared loss} ($\mathcal{Y} = \mathbb{R}$, $\ell(y, c) = (y - c)^2$). The per-leaf objective $\sum_{i \in I_m}(y_i - c)^2$ is a strictly convex quadratic in $c$, minimized at the leaf mean $\bar y_m := n_m^{-1} \sum_{i \in I_m} y_i$.
\item \emph{0/1 loss} ($\mathcal{Y} = \{1, \ldots, K\}$, $\ell(y, c) = \indc\{y \neq c\}$). Writing $n_{m, k} := |\{i \in I_m : y_i = k\}|$ for per-leaf class counts, the per-leaf objective is $\sum_{i \in I_m} \indc\{y_i \neq c\} = n_m - n_{m, c}$, minimized at the modal class $c_m^* \in \arg\max_{k} n_{m, k}$ (ties broken arbitrarily).
\item \emph{Cross-entropy} ($\mathcal{Y} = \Delta^{K-1}$, the probability simplex; $\ell(y, p) = -\sum_{k} \indc\{y = k\} \log p_k$). The per-leaf objective $-\sum_{k} n_{m, k} \log p_k$ is minimized at the empirical class proportions $\hat p_{m, k} = n_{m, k} / n_m$.
\end{itemize}
\end{example}

\begin{proof}[Proof of the cross-entropy case in Example~\ref{ex:closed-form-leaf}]
The objective $-\sum_{k} n_{m, k} \log p_k$ is convex in $p$ on the simplex (taking $0 \log 0 = 0$). The Lagrangian for $\sum_{k} p_k = 1$ is
\[
  \mathcal{L}(p, \mu) \;=\; -\sum_{k} n_{m, k} \log p_k \;+\; \mu\Bigl(\sum_{k} p_k - 1\Bigr),
\]
and stationarity gives $-n_{m, k} / p_k + \mu = 0$, hence $p_k = n_{m, k} / \mu$. The simplex constraint fixes $\mu = n_m$, yielding $p_k^* = n_{m, k} / n_m$.
\end{proof}

Lemma~\ref{lem:perleaf-decomp} and Example~\ref{ex:closed-form-leaf} reduce tree learning to choosing the partition; leaf values then follow in closed form. The remaining problem,
\[
  \min_{T} \; \frac{1}{n} \sum_{m=1}^{|T|} \min_{c \in \mathcal{Y}} \sum_{i \in I_m} \ell(y_i, c),
\]
is over the combinatorial set of binary trees on $\mathcal{X}$.

\subsection{Why greedy splits}\label{sec:5.1.3}

The minimization at the end of \S 5.1.2 has no efficient exact solver: even ``find the smallest tree that fits'' is NP-complete.

\begin{theorem}[Hyafil and Rivest, 1976]\label{thm:hyafil-rivest}
The decision problem \textsc{Min-Tree} is NP-complete:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textsc{Input.} A finite training sample $\{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^{n} \subset \{0, 1\}^p \times \{0, 1\}$ and a positive integer $K$.
\item \textsc{Question.} Does there exist a binary decision tree with at most $K$ leaves that correctly classifies every training row?
\end{itemize}
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
\textbf{In NP.} Given a candidate tree $T$, verify in time $O(K \cdot n \cdot p)$ that $T$ has at most $K$ leaves and classifies every training row correctly.

\textbf{NP-hard via Set Cover.} \textsc{Set-Cover} is NP-complete (Karp, 1972; Hyafil and Rivest's original reduction used Exact Cover by 3-Sets):
\begin{itemize}
\item \textsc{Input.} A universe $U = \{u_1, \ldots, u_q\}$, a sub-collection $\mathcal{S} = \{S_1, \ldots, S_m\}$ of subsets of $U$ with $\bigcup_{j} S_j = U$, and a positive integer $k$.
\item \textsc{Question.} Does there exist $\mathcal{S}' \subseteq \mathcal{S}$ with $|\mathcal{S}'| \leqslant k$ such that $\bigcup_{S \in \mathcal{S}'} S = U$?
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Construction.} From $(U, \mathcal{S}, k)$, build a \textsc{Min-Tree} instance with $p = m$ features (one per set), $n = q + 1$ rows, and bound $K = k + 1$:
\begin{itemize}
\item For each $u \in U$, one positive row $a_u \in \{0, 1\}^m$ with $(a_u)_j = 1$ iff $u \in S_j$.
\item One negative row $b = (0, \ldots, 0)$.
\end{itemize}
The construction is polynomial in the input size.

\textbf{Cover $\Rightarrow$ tree.} Suppose $\mathcal{S}' = \{S_{j_1}, \ldots, S_{j_{k'}}\}$ covers $U$ with $k' \leqslant k$. Build a \emph{comb tree}: along the leftmost path, test features $j_1, \ldots, j_{k'}$ in order; the right child of each test is a positive leaf, and the left child after $j_{k'}$ is a negative leaf. Leaf count: $k' + 1 \leqslant K$.

Every entry of $b$ is $0$, so $b$ takes left at every test and lands at the negative leaf. For each $a_u$, let $t$ be the smallest index in $\{1, \ldots, k'\}$ with $u \in S_{j_t}$ (such $t$ exists because $\mathcal{S}'$ covers $U$); then $(a_u)_{j_s} = 0$ for $s < t$ and $(a_u)_{j_t} = 1$, so $a_u$ takes left at $j_1, \ldots, j_{t-1}$, right at $j_t$, and lands at a positive leaf.

\textbf{Tree $\Rightarrow$ cover.} Suppose $T$ has $|T| \leqslant K = k+1$ leaves and classifies every training row correctly. Let $j_1, \ldots, j_t$ be the features tested along $b$'s root-to-leaf path. Every $b_j = 0$, so $b$ takes left at every test; its leaf has label $0$.

For each $u \in U$, $a_u$ must reach a positive leaf. From the root, $a_u$ stays with $b$ as long as $u \notin S_{j_s}$ on the tests $j_s$ encountered. If $u \notin S_{j_s}$ for every $s$, then $a_u$ ends at $b$'s (negative) leaf, contradicting $a_u$'s positive label. So some $s$ has $u \in S_{j_s}$, and $\mathcal{S}' := \{S_{j_1}, \ldots, S_{j_t}\}$ (de-duplicated) covers $U$.

Each of the $t$ internal nodes on $b$'s path has a right child rooting a subtree with at least one leaf; with the leaf at the end of $b$'s path, $|T| \geqslant t + 1$. Combined with $|T| \leqslant k + 1$, $t \leqslant k$, so $|\mathcal{S}'| \leqslant t \leqslant k$.
\end{proof}

\begin{example}[Reduction in action]\label{ex:setcover-reduction}
Take $U = \{u_1, u_2, u_3\}$ and $\mathcal{S} = \{S_1, S_2, S_3\}$ with $S_1 = \{u_1, u_2\}$, $S_2 = \{u_2, u_3\}$, $S_3 = \{u_1, u_3\}$. The minimum cover has $k = 2$. The reduction sets $K = 3$ and produces
\[
  a_{u_1} = (1, 0, 1), \quad a_{u_2} = (1, 1, 0), \quad a_{u_3} = (0, 1, 1), \quad b = (0, 0, 0).
\]
The cover $\{S_1, S_2\}$ gives the comb tree of Figure~\ref{fig:setcover-comb}: test $f_1$ then $f_2$ down the leftmost path, positive leaves on each right side, negative leaf at the bottom. Three leaves; all four rows classified. No two-leaf tree (one internal test) works: for any feature $f_j$, the left child of the test on $f_j$ contains $b$ together with the $a_{u_i}$ for which $u_i \notin S_j$.
\end{example}

\begin{figure}[!htbp]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    level distance=2.5cm,
    level 1/.style={sibling distance=6cm},
    level 2/.style={sibling distance=4cm},
    % 將原本的 every node 改名為自訂的 treenode，避免干擾線條上的文字標籤
    treenode/.style={draw, rectangle, rounded corners, align=center, fill=white, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=1cm},
    edge from parent/.style={draw, -latex, thick},
    % 讓葉節點繼承 treenode 的大小與框線設定
    leaf_pos/.style={treenode, fill=green!10, font=\bfseries},
    leaf_neg/.style={treenode, fill=red!10, font=\bfseries},
    % 縮小文字標籤，只保留白色底色以增加易讀性
    edge_label/.style={fill=white, font=\small, inner sep=2pt}
]

% Root Node
\node[treenode] (root) {Test $f_1$ (Cover $S_1$)}
    % Left Child (f1 = 0)
    child {
        node[treenode] (f2) {Test $f_2$ (Cover $S_2$)}
        % Left Child of f2 (f2 = 0)
        child {
            node[leaf_neg] {Label = 0 \\[-0.5ex] {\small (Catches $b$)}}
            edge from parent node[edge_label, left=2pt] {$f_2 = 0$}
        }
        % Right Child of f2 (f2 = 1)
        child {
            node[leaf_pos] {Label = 1 \\[-0.5ex] {\small (Catches $a_{u_3}$)}}
            edge from parent node[edge_label, right=2pt] {$f_2 = 1$}
        }
